    /** New implementation.
     * Here, I need to accept the Customer entity object instead of CustomerDto object.
     * Inside this method, delete all that code related to the CustomerDto object and CustomerMapper related code also we can delete.
     * Now, using the mobile number present inside the Customer entity object, we can check if there is already a customer available. If available, I am going to throw this CustonerALreadyExistsException. Otherwise, we are going to simply save the data into the DB.
     * You may be wondering why are we doing the validation here one more time? Reason - we have already done this very similar validation on the aggregate side - if you check with the constructor of the class CustomerAggregate - we are doing the same validation there as soon as someone publishes this CreateCustomerCommand. Since we are doing that validation already there, whatever we are doing in the CustomerServiceImpl class on the projection side might look redundant. But my instructor would always request me to perform the validation on the read side as well! Why? Reason - sometimes if your event is being consumed multiple times for whatever reason - in such scenarios, you don't want to insert multiple similar customer details. So, to avoid such scenario, you need to perform this validation during the Customer Creation on the read DB as well.
     * With this now, we have completed all the logic related to the CustomerCreated Event.
     * */
    @Override
    public void createCustomer(Customer customerEntity) {
        Optional<Customer> optionalCustomer = customerRepository.findByMobileNumberAndActiveSw(
                customerEntity.getMobileNumber(), true);
        if (optionalCustomer.isPresent()) {
            throw new CustomerAlreadyExistsException("Customer already registered with given mobileNumber "
                    + customerEntity.getMobileNumber());
        }
        Customer savedCustomer = customerRepository.save(customerEntity);
    }

    @Override
    public CustomerDto fetchCustomer(String mobileNumber) {
        Customer customer = customerRepository.findByMobileNumberAndActiveSw(mobileNumber, true).orElseThrow(
                () -> new ResourceNotFoundException("Customer", "mobileNumber", mobileNumber)
        );
        CustomerDto customerDto = CustomerMapper.mapToCustomerDto(customer, new CustomerDto());
        return customerDto;
    }

